2. Design and Development Methodology
Our team followed the Agile methodology (Scrum-style iterations) as planned in Assignment 1. This approach proved appropriate because it allowed us to build the Guest and Administrator interfaces as separate sprints while our understanding of the UI/UX flows evolved.

The methodology did not fundamentally change, but it was refined through the use of Git for version control. By using a shared repository, we were able to divide work efficiently: one team member focused on the core project scaffolding and repository management, while others developed specific Guest and Administrator components in parallel. This iterative approach allowed us to identify and resolve integration issues, such as version control conflicts and runtime errors, before the final submission.

3. Front-End Technologies and Responsibilities
Technologies and Justification
React.js & Vite: We chose React for its component-based architecture, which made it simple to divide the "User Dashboard" and "Admin Dashboard" into independent, manageable parts. Vite was used for its fast development server and "Hot Module Replacement," allowing for real-time UI updates.

CSS3: Used for styling, specifically implementing the Purple and Black theme consistent with the user's preferences.

JavaScript (ES6): Used for client-side validations (e.g., email format and character limits) and managing mock data state.

